comment: The predicate toLocation is used to indicate the ending point of a particular movement. (toLocation MOVE LOC) means that LOC is where the objectMoving in MOVE (a Movement_TranslationEvent) is found when the event MOVE ends; the final location of the objectMoving in that event is LOC. The objectMoving may or may not be Stationary at LOC. If MOVE is a single-pathway translation (see Translation_SingleTrajectory), then every objectMoving in it is found at LOC when MOVE ends. If MOVE has multiple movers and multiple pathways (see Translation_MultiTrajectory), then at least some of the objectMoving(s) can be found at LOC at the end of MOVE. If MOVE is a fluid flow (see FluidFlow_Translation), then at least some portion of the fluid objectMoving can be found at location LOC at the end of MOVE. See also motionPathway_Complete, pathConnects.
label: destination

comment:
A MetaPredicate for specifying the argument-place(s) with respect to which a given FunctionalPredicate (q.v) is "functional" in a strict sense. (strictlyFunctionalInArgs PRED N) means that PRED is strictly functional in its Nth argument-place. That is, for any particular way of fixing all of PRED's other arguments, there will be at most one thing that, if taken as the Nth argument, would result in a true sentence. For example, biologicalMother is strictly functional in its second argument, as nothing has more than one biological mother.

In most cases, the entry-format (see argFormat) of a strictly functional argument-place should be singleEntryFormatInArgs (q.v.). Obviously, the specified integer N must be less than or equal to the arity (see arity) of PRED. Note that, for some ways of fixing the other arguments, there might be nothing that would yield a true sentence when put in PRED's functional argument-place. For example, dictator is functional in its second argument because a given country can have at most one dictator at a given time; but of course some countries have no dictator.

For a more general predicate that encompasses a looser sense in which a predicate's argument-place might be called "functional", see functionalInArgs.
label: Strictly Functional In Args
strictlyFunctionalInArgs

Each latitude zone is 8 degrees high, and is lettered starting from "C" at 80 S latitude, increasing up the (English) alphabet up to "X", omitting the letters "I" and "O" (because of their similarity to the digits one and zero). comment: A SpatialPredicate and a specialization of hasBeenIn (q.v.). (usualLocationOfObject OBJ PLACE) means that OBJ is usually or primarily (and perhaps permanently) located at PLACE. This does not entail that OBJ is at PLACE at any particular time, as OBJ may be away from its usual location at various time. (Cf. objectFoundInLocation). Nor does it even entail that OBJ is at PLACE most of the time. Rather, it means that PLACE is OBJ's "home base" in some sense. Thus, usualLocationOfObject is more a normative than a temporally quantitative relation. Its specializations include physicalQuarters, residesInRegion, residesInDwelling, and hasHabitat.
label: Usual Location Of Object
usualLocationOfObject

This predicate is used to state that things of one given type always temporally intersect things of another given type. (temporallyIntersects_TypeType TYPE1 TYPE2) means that for every instance INST1 of TYPE1, there is an instance INST2 of TYPE2 such that (temporallyIntersects INST1 INST2). For example, (temporallyIntersects_TypeType January Wednesday) states (correctly) that each January overlaps some Wednesday. Note that this predicate is _not_ symmetric; e.g. (temporallyIntersects_TypeType Wednesday January) does not hold. comment: (vehicleRange VEH DIST) means that DIST is the maximum distance that can be translated using the vehicle VEH, without intermediate refueling and assuming typical usage and normal operating parameters. We intend this to be a very strict measure, an important thing to keep in mind since the vernacular sense of 'effective range' is much looser. In point of fact, the vehicleRange is a key tool in calculating what the effective operating range of a fuel-powered vehicle is. If, e.g., we are dealing with a case of a vehicle that operates from a fixed base of operations, such as a FighterPlane, the effective operating range will ordinarily be one-half the absolute vehicleRange, since ordinarily provision will be made for the plane's returning to base. However, we may well want to consider special cases where this provision is not made. Conversely, in cases where aerial refueling is a possibility, the actual effective operating range will be some multiple of the vehicleRange, or may even be indefinite.
label: Vehicle Range
vehicleRange

comment:
A ComplexTemporalPredicate that relates a TemporalThing to any ContinuousTimeInterval (q.v.) that it temporally subsumes. (temporallyContinuousDuring TEMP INTERVAL) means that TEMP temporallySubsumes the continuous chunk of time INTERVAL. That is, TEMP subsumes every time-interval between the startingPoint and endingPoint of INTERVAL. Thus, there is no time-interval between the start and end of INTERVAL during which TEMP does not exist (if a SomethingExisting) or occur (if an Event) or obtain (if a StaticSituation) or which TEMP does not have as one of its timeSlices (if a TimeInterval).

Note that a given thing might be temporally continuous during some but not all of the continuous intervals between its own startingPoint and endingPoint. A TemporallyContinuousThing (q.v.), however, is continuous during all such intervals.
label: Temporally Continuous During
temporallyContinuousDuring

comment: (versionOfJobPosition JOB RELATION) means that the version of JobPosition JOB is the HasPositionRelationship RELATION. An instance of JobPosition can have more than one version because the same JobPosition can be filled successively by more than one person. A different HasPositionRelationship is created each time a different person fills the same JobPosition JOB. Each of these HasPositionRelationships bear the relation versionOfJobPosition to the same JobPosition, although these relations hold at different time intervals. Two different people cannot bear the versionOfJobPosition relation to the same JobPosition during the same time interval. For example, suppose Cycorp has a JobPosition, OntologicalEngineer01. At t1, the position is open (see JobOpen). At t2, David Smith is hired to fill this position (see JobFilled) . At t2, a HasPositionRelationship, OntologicalEngineer01DS begins, the relation between David Smith and Cycorp. At t2, it's true that (versionOfJobPosition OntologicalEngineer01 OntologicalEngineer01DS). At t3, David Smith resigns. At t4, Kevin Jones is hired to fill the JobPosition OntologicalEngineer01, and a new HasPositionRelationship, OntologicalEngineer01KJ is created. At t4, it's true that (versionOfJobPosition OntologicalEngineer01 OntologicalEngineer01KJ). See SomethingToWear for its specializations of things that can be worn. See wearsClothing, which relates entire wearers, rather than body parts, to items worn. comment: A test, by definition, involves comparing the results of the test with some expected or 'correct answer'. testAnswersCycL_Wanted should be used in the case where we cannot predict the entire set of answers that should be retrieved, but wish to ensure that our expected answers are among those retrieved. (testAnswersCycL_Wanted TEST BINDINGSET) states that BINDINGSET is one of the answers (a set of ELInferenceBindings) that should be retrieved by submitting TEST's formula as a CycL query. For each correct answer that we expect to get, there should be one assertion using testAnswersCycL_Wanted. Taken together, these assertions record the minimal set of binding sets necessary for test success. If any BINDINGSET is missing from the result, a test failure will be signalled. However, the presence of additional binding sets within the result is not an indication of test failure.
label: Test Answers Cyc L Wanted
testAnswersCycL-Wanted

This predicate relates a translational movement event to the accumulated total displacement by the primaryObjectMoving in that event. Note that DIST is the net change in position by the object, not its total distance travelled; so if the motionPathway_Complete of MOVE is a round trip a mile each way, the totalDisplacement would be zero miles, not two. comment: (subTopicFnTakesInstances SUBTOPFN COLL) means that, within the context in which this assertion is made, each instance INST of COLL is a good, sensible argument for the SubTopicFunction SUBTOPFN. For example, (subTopicFnTakesInstances FanSiteFn ActorInMovies) means that every instance ACTOR of ActorInMovies is a good, sensible argument for FanSiteFn -- it is reasonable to talk about fan sites for that instance. Note that this assertion does not mean that for every instance ACTOR there is at least one such site. It means only that it is reasonable and normal (within the context in which the assertion is made) to ask, assert, or otherwise reason about fan sites for ACTOR (in contrast, say, to the abnormality of asking, asserting, or otherwise reasoning about maps of ACTOR or designs for building ACTOR) .

comment:
This predicate relates objects to the transportation events in which they facilitate movement. (transporter MOVE OBJ) means that SolidTangibleThing OBJ enables or facilitates the conveyance of the transportees in the TransportationEvent MOVE. OBJ is an objectMoving in MOVE that moves along with the transportees. OBJ will generally hold, support, contain, pull, or push the transportees throughout the MOVE Event. OBJ may or may not be the providerOfMotiveForce in the event MOVE. If OBJ stays with each primaryObjectMoving from the fromLocation to the toLocation, moving along the same trajectory, then it is also a primaryObjectMoving.

If OBJ facilitates the motion of the primaryObjectMoving but does not itself engage in translational motion it is merely the conveyor of the action, and the role conveyor_Stationary should be asserted. If it is unclear whether the conveyor is stationary or not, the role conveyor_Generic is used. Specializations of the role transporter should be used when possible: although automobiles are transporters in many events, they should normally have the more specific role designation of vehicle because they are also instances of TransportationDevice_Vehicle. When a car is being towed by a tow truck, the car is just a transporter of any of its contents while the tow truck is the vehicle of that event. An additional role designation for some transporters -- those which are PhysicalDevices -- is deviceUsed; e.g., the use of crutches in hobbling or ice skates in skating. See the comment on TransportationEvent. Note that an organism may be a transportees in a Bicycle riding or Skating event as well as being the providerOfMotiveForce in such cases.
label: transporter

A FirstOrderCollectionPredicate that is a specialization of temporallySubsumedBy_TypeType (q.v.) and a type-level inverse correlate of subEvents (q.v.). This predicate is used to state that events of one given type always have events of another given type as superevents. (superEventTypes SUBTYPE SUPERTYPE) means that for every instance SUBINST of SUBTYPE, there is an instance SUPERINST of SUPERTYPE, such that (subEvents SUPERINST SUBINST). For example, (superEventTypes Sentencing_Legal Trial_Criminal) means that every legal sentencing is a subevent of a criminal trial.

See also subEventTypes; and note that (subEventTypes SUPERTYPE SUBTYPE) is neither necessary nor sufficient for (superEventTypes SUBTYPE SUPERTYPE).
label: Super Event Types
superEventTypes

comment:
A binary predicate that is used to show how a complex interconvertible-unit-type can be analyzed in terms of more basic unit-types. unitTypeDimensionalAnalysis relates a non-primitive InterconvertibleUnitType (q.v.) to a set of Lists that represents an equivalent "product" of FundamentalUnitTypes.

(unitTypeDimensionalAnalysis UNITTYPE PRODUCT-SET) means that any MeasurableQuantity (q.v.) returned by an instance of UNITTYPE can be converted to (i.e. represented as) a product of quantities measured in units of the (fundamental) types in PRODUCT-SET. More precisely, each element of PRODUCT-SET is of the form (TheList FUND-UNITTYPE EXPONENT), and so PRODUCT-SET itself is of the form 

  (TheSet
    (TheList FUND-UNITTYPE-1 EXPONENT-1)
    (TheList FUND-UNITTYPE-2 EXPONENT-2)
    . . .
    (TheList FUND-UNITTYPE-n EXPONENT-n)).

Hence, (unitTypeDimensionalAnalysis UNITTYPE PRODUCT-SET) means that UNITTYPE is equivalent to (put schematically) 

  (FUND-UNITTYPE-1 ^ EXPONENT-1) *
  (FUND-UNITTYPE-2 ^ EXPONENT-2) *
  . . . *
  (FUND-UNITTYPE-n ^ EXPONENT-n).

In other words: for any UnitOfMeasure (q.v.) function UNIT that is an instance of UNITTYPE, (UNIT 1) (i.e. the quantity one-UNIT) is equal to a quantity of the form 

  (TimesFn
    (ScalarExponentFn (FUND-UNIT-1 1) EXPONENT-1)
    (ScalarExponentFn (FUND-UNIT-2 1) EXPONENT-2)
    . . .
    (ScalarExponentFn (FUND-UNIT-n 1) EXPONENT-n)) ,

where each FUND-UNIT-i is some instance of FUND-UNITTYPE-i (for 1 <= i <= n).

For example, 

  (unitTypeDimensionalAnalysis
    UnitOfSpeed
    (TheSet
      (TheList UnitOfDistance 1)
      (TheList UnitOfTime -1)))

means that each UnitOfSpeed is obtainable by "dividing" a UnitOfDistance by a UnitOfTime (e.g. MilesPerHour = (PerFn Mile HoursDuration)). Put more simply: speed is distance over time.
label: Unit Type Dimensional Analysis
unitTypeDimensionalAnalysis

comment:
A RelativeLocationalPredicate and specialization of near that holds between certain tangible objects. (touches OBJ1 OBJ2) means that OBJ1 and OBJ2 are in contact, either directly or indirectly. Two spatial things are directly in contact just in case there is nothing between them; to indicate that such a situation obtains between two spatial things, use the specialization touches_Directly. Two spatial things touch indirectly if there is only a very thin object or substance between them. Here 'very thin' means that the distance between the surfaces of the two spatial things is very much less than the distance between their center points.

Here are some examples in which touches holds: an airplane touches the air around it; my feet touch the floor (even though I am wearing shoes); a blanket touches the person sleeping under it (even if there is a sheet); a hovercraft touches the water (even though a cushion of air is between it and the water).
label: touching an object
touches

(trajectoryPassesThrough MOVE LOC) means that the trajectory (see trajectory_Complete) of the object moving (see objectMoving) OBJ in the Translation_SingleTrajectory MOVE passes through the location (see EnduringThing_Localized) LOC. Here "passes through LOC" implies that, in the course of moving from its fromLocation to its toLocation, OBJ first arrives in and then leaves LOC.

Note that LOC is not constrained to be spatiallyDisjoint with this from-location or to-location; LOC might even subsume (see spatiallySubsumes) either of them. Thus, if (say) LOC subsumes the from-location, OBJ must first leave LOC, then arrive back in LOC, and then leave LOC again in order to pass through it.

Also note that LOC must be Stationary during MOVE, relative to the associated FrameOfReference.

(translatesFromTo MOTION OBJECT) means that OBJECT undergoes place to place motion (technically referred to as translation) such that it moves from the 'from' and to the 'to' locations which are strongly associated with MOTION. More formally, a short time before MOTION starts, OBJECT is located at the fromLocation of MOTION. A short time after MOTION ends, OBJECT is located at the toLocation of MOTION. Given MOTION, all values on fromLocation must spatially intersect. Likewise, given MOTION, all values on toLocation must spatially intersect. This is because if MOTION is an event in which there are multiple non-intersecting toLocations (as is the case with scattering or distribution events) then it would not make sense to use translatesFromTo. Consider the following examples. It would be impossible for a plane to fly (i.e. play the role of translatesFromTo) to both LaGuardiaAirport and KennedyAirport. However, it would be possible for both LaGuardiaAirport and CityOfNewYorkNY to be toLocations since LaGuardiaAirport spatially intersects with CityOfNewYorkNY. Although toLocation and fromLocation must be spatially intersecting, pathways (see motionPathway_Complete) may be distinct. Consider the event in which several flocks of birds migrate from Alaska to Mexico. Each flock may leave and arrive at the roughly the same time. Each flock may leave from and arrive at the same general locations. However, they probably take different pathways en route. translatesFromTo can be used to relate that single group migration event to the several flocks, or even the numerous birds participating in the event.
label: Translates From To
translatesFromTo

comment: (subOrgs_MaterialSupport SUPER SUB) means that SUB is in an organizational relationship with SUPER in which SUPER is ordinarily responsible for providing most of the materials, supplies, and logistic support or 'infrastructure support' for SUB's activities, and SUB depends on SUPER for this support. Such support may include equipment, facilities, fuel, and supply and/or resupply of goods and materiel. (Different organizations may supply services or money, or may have command over SUB. These are not indicated by this predicate.) For example, if a military field reconnaissance unit ordinarily calls upon a logistics unit for most of its materiel support--e.g., for mess equipment or for ammunition, then the logistics unit has the reconnaissance unit as one of its subOrgs_MaterialSupport dependents. Similarly, if a company COMP offers its labs, facilities and lab supplies to a research team TEAM from a university, then (subOrgs_MaterialSupport COMP TEAM) is true, even if money for the team's salaries comes from the university. SUB need not be directly supported by SUPER, -- it could also be several steps down in the metrials distribution chain. (See also subOrgs_Financial, subOrgs_AdministrativeServiceSupport, and subOrgs_Command.)
label: material support suborganization
subOrgs-MaterialSupport

comment: vulnerabilityDatabaseURLFormatString is used to specify the general format of the URL string for reports of faults and vulnerabilities in on-line databases. To generate an actual URL, it should be the case that all that need be added to the string are characters that map to the ID string for the fault or vulnerability. For example, "http://www.cert.org/advisories/~A.html " is an appropriate vulnerabilityDatabaseURLFormatString for CERTAdvisoryDatabase because, to generate the URL for a CERT entry, it is necessary only to substitute the ID of the fault (say, "CA-2000-13") for the occurrence of "~A" in the vulnerabilityDatabaseURLFormatString to generate the appropriate URL ("http://www.cert.org/advisories/CA-2000-13.html "). Similarly, "http://www.securityfocus.com/bid/~A " is an appropriate vulnerabilityDatabaseURLFormatString for BugtraqFaultDatabase because it is necessary only to substitute the ID of the fault (say "219") for the occurrence of "~A" in the vulnerabilityDatabaseURLFormatString to generate the appropriate URL ("http://www.securityfocus.com/bid/219 ").

comment:
An expression of the form (testFollowupTestFormula_Some TEST FORMULA) is used to partially describe a followup test that should be run on the #$KBContentTest-FullySpecified TEST to test the properties of the answers returned by TEST. Specifically, FORMULA is both an CycLOpenSentence and a CycLSentence_Askable. This formula will support the creation of a second test that would have the same query formula as the CycLQuerySpecification of TEST but with FORMULA conjoined to the relevant query, within the scope of any explicit quantifiers. (In the case of a hypothetical query, it would be conjoined to the consequent of the implication.) As an example, assume that TEST has the hypothetical query 
  (implies
    (likesAsFriend ?X ?X)
    (likesAsFriend ?X ?Y))
The assertion (testFollowupTestFormula_Some TEST (equals ?Y ?X)) would generate the follow up query formula:
  (implies
    (likesAsFriend ?X ?X)
    (and
      (likesAsFriend ?X ?Y)
      (equals ?X ?Y)))
The CycLQuerySpecification of the followup test will assume the same parameter settings as the CycLQuerySpecification for TEST, most significantly the InferenceMicrotheoryParameter. The success of TEST requires that the set of bindings returned by the followup query is non-empty. Furthermore, this predicate assumes that the introduction of FORMULA does not cause the query formula for the followup query to have a different set of free variables. See also testFollowupTestFormula_All and testFollowupTestFormula_None.
label: Test Followup Test Formula Some
testFollowupTestFormula-Some

comment: (subOrgs_AdministrativeServiceSupport SUPER SUB) means that SUB is in an organizational relationship with SUPER in which SUPER is ordinarily responsible for providing most of the administrative services or 'service support' for SUB's activities, and SUB depends on SUPER for this support. Such support may include engineering, programming, legal, personnel, or religious services, or SUB's primary planning, analysis, or advice. (Different organizations may supply material goods or money, or may have command over SUB. These are not necessarily indicated by this predicate.) For example, if a military field reconnaissance unit ordinarily calls upon another unit for most administrative support services --e.g., for maintenance, programming computers, legal issues, personnel management, etc.-- then the engineering unit has the reconnaissance unit as one of its subOrgs_AdministrativeServiceSupport dependents. Similarly, if a company COMP offers its legal department's advice and health coverage to a research team TEAM from a university, then (subOrgs_AdministrativeServiceSupport COMP TEAM) is true, even if money for the team's salaries comes from the university. (See also subOrgs_Financial, subOrgs_MaterialSupport, and subOrgs_Command.)

comment: (typeHasStyle TYPE STYLE) means that every instance of collection, TYPE, has (in some sense) STYLE. This is one of the broadest predicates that can be used to ascribe a style to a type of thing. This is not equivalent to (relationAllInstance hasStyle TYPE STYLE). This latter assertion entails that every instance of Type is an instance of STYLE. This is a somewhat weaker relation. Consider the relation between a type of music and its genre: (typeHasStyle ReggaeMusic MusicalComposition_Reggae) holds but ReggaeMusic is a specialization of Music which is a specialization of InformationBearingThing. InformationBearingThing is disjoint from MusicalComposition of which MusicalComposition_Reggae is a specialization. Hence, (relationAllInstance hasStyle ReggaeMusic MusicalComposition_Reggae) is false. Avoid using this predicate in favor of more specific ones.
label: Type Has Style
typeHasStyle

Note that the instances of SUBCOLTYPE and COLTYPE mentioned in the above definition might or might not actually be reified in the Cyc Knowledge Base. Thus, the above example would still be true even if the collection FeminineObject were not represented in the KB.

(surfaceFeatureOfObject OBJ ATT) means that the 'salient' surface of OBJ has the attribute ATT. Which surface is 'salient' is a function of context in the broad sense of the term context. For elements of ConvexTangibleObject, the outside surface is salient. Thus, we can assert that, e.g., (surfaceFeatureOfObject Cavity001 #$Concave). comment:
An expression of the form (testFollowupTestFormula_None TEST FORMULA) is used to partially describe a followup test that should be run on the #$KBContentTest-FullySpecified TEST to test the properties of the answers returned by TEST. Specifically, FORMULA is both an CycLOpenSentence and a CycLSentence_Askable. This formula will support the creation of a second test that would have the same query formula as the CycLQuerySpecification of TEST but with FORMULA conjoined to the relevant query, within the scope of any explicit quantifiers. (In the case of a hypothetical query, it would be conjoined to the consequent of the implication.) As an example, assume that TEST has the hypothetical query 
  (implies
    (likesAsFriend ?X ?X)
    (likesAsFriend ?X ?Y))
The assertion (testFollowupTestFormula_None TEST (isa ?Y NonPersonAnimal)) would generate the followup query formula:
  (implies
    (likesAsFriend ?X ?X)
    (and
      (likesAsFriend ?X ?Y)
      (isa ?Y NonPersonAnimal)))
The CycLQuerySpecification of the followup test will assume the same parameter settings as the CycLQuerySpecification for TEST, most significantly the InferenceMicrotheoryParameter. The success of TEST requires that no bindings are returned by the followup test. That is, this test specification can be used to screen the answers to the first query so as to ensure that certain classes of answers are not returned. It is assumed that the introduction of FORMULA does not cause the query formula for the followup query to have a different set of free variables. See also testFollowupTestFormula_All and testFollowupTestFormula_Some.
label: Test Followup Test Formula None
testFollowupTestFormula-None
